p.text:
The “seven persons” criterion substitutes an arbitrary, but clear, threshold requirement for the use of the representation procedures (subject to the discretion conferred by CPA 
s 164
). It replaces the “numerous persons” criterion that characterised some earlier provisions. That criterion gave rise to difficulties in situations where there was a paucity of evidence to establish the likely existence of any “represented” parties: Campbells Cash and Carry Pty Ltd v Fostif Pty Ltd (2006) 229 CLR 386; 229 ALR 58; [2006] HCA 41;  BC200606677 at [57]–[60] , [214]–[228] (“opt in” class definition); or to be satisfied of the real potential affectation of a significant number of people: Cauvin v Philip Morris Pty Ltd [2003] NSWSC 631;  BC200304265  — only “five” potential represented parties).
